title: San Leandro Marina Development Faces Hurdles Despite Approval
---
body:

#### text-block ####
text:

The East Bay suburb of San Leandro may see a revitalized marina as early as next year, as a multiphase mixed-use project by Cal-Coast Development nears the end of its preliminary planning stage. Monarch Bay’s 40 acres of apartments, retail, office space, and amenities has been approved by the San Leandro City Council, and will soon be reviewed by the San Francisco Bay Conservation and Development Commission (BCDC). As of 2011, the state agency requires new construction to plan for withstanding rising sea levels due to climate change. 

Cal-Coast’s most immediate plans include 150,000 square feet of office space, a 468-space parking garage, two restaurants, and a kayak rental facility. A residential component would not be included until the second phase, with several four-story buildings providing 160 rental units and 61 condominiums. An average of 1.5 parking spaces per residential unit is planned, with at least 587 additional public parking spaces planned for the shoreline. San Leandro [amended](https://sanleandro.legistar.com/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=2285006&GUID=B3C57382-78E9-4041-98FB-AE0CB9011EE8&Options=&Search=) its general plan for the area last year to accommodate the project’s mixed-use components in its zoning code.

Resistance to the project has coalesced behind a lawsuit filed by the Coalition for the San Leandro Shoreline against the city and the developer. The coalition is led by the neighboring Marina Inn. Opponents cited fears of displacing local residents and losing views of the Bay when speaking to the [East Bay Times](http://www.eastbaytimes.com/2016/09/29/san-leandro-shoreline-project-could-break-ground-next-year/).
